listings.label: Tennis for Two (REPRODUCTION)
listings.description:
Tennis for Two (also known as Computer Tennis) is a sports video game, which simulates a game of tennis, and was one of the first games developed. American physicist William Higinbotham designed the game in 1958 for display at the Brookhaven National Laboratory's annual public exhibition. The game was very popular during the three-day exhibition, with players lining up to see the game, especially high school students.

This reproduction was made in 1995. The reconstruction took about three months, partially because the parts were not readily available.

listings.description:
Product Description

Disney’s The Lion King, directed by Jon Favreau, journeys to the African savanna, where a future king is born. Simba idolizes his father, King Mufasa, and takes to heart his own royal destiny. But not everyone in the kingdom celebrates the new cub’s arrival. Scar, Mufasa’s brother—and former heir to the throne—has plans of his own. The battle for Pride Rock is ravaged with betrayal, tragedy and drama, ultimately resulting in Simba’s exile. listings.label: Tennis for Two (REPRODUCTION)
listings.description:
Tennis for Two (also known as Computer Tennis) is a sports video game, which simulates a game of tennis, and was one of the first games developed. American physicist William Higinbotham designed the game in 1958 for display at the Brookhaven National Laboratory's annual public exhibition. The game was very popular during the three-day exhibition, with players lining up to see the game, especially high school students.

This reproduction was made in 1995. The reconstruction took about three months, partially because the parts were not readily available.
